02:50.045 --> 02:52.422
<i>One of the things
to bear in mind is that</i>

02:52.505 --> 02:55.342
when we think about slavery,
it was an economic system.

02:55.425 --> 02:59.722
And the demise of slavery
at the end of the Civil War

02:59.805 --> 03:04.101
left the Southern economy in tatters.
Uh, and so this presented a big question.

03:04.184 --> 03:07.104
There are four million people
who were formerly property,

03:07.187 --> 03:10.023
and they were formerly
kind of the integral part

03:10.107 --> 03:12.943
of the economic production system
in the South.

03:13.026 --> 03:14.527
And now those people are free.

03:18.365 --> 03:20.909
<i>And so what do you do with these people?</i>

03:24.162 --> 03:26.164
<i>How do you rebuild your economy?</i>

03:28.166 --> 03:32.755
The 13th Amendment loophole
was immediately exploited.

03:32.838 --> 03:37.259
After the Civil War,
African Americans were arrested en masse.

03:37.342 --> 03:40.553
<i>It was our nation's first prison boom.</i>

03:43.431 --> 03:46.309
<i>You were basically a slave again.
The 13th Amendment says that</i>

03:46.393 --> 03:48.233
"Except for criminals,
everybody else is free."

03:48.311 --> 03:52.232
Well, now if you're criminalized,
that doesn't apply to you.

03:52.315 --> 03:55.235
<i>They were arrested
for extremely minor crimes,</i>

03:55.318 --> 03:58.321
<i>like loitering or vagrancy.</i>

04:00.365 --> 04:03.493
And they had to provide labor

04:03.576 --> 04:07.205
to rebuild the economy
of the South after the Civil War.

04:13.461 --> 04:16.757
<i>What you got after that
was a rapid transition</i>

04:16.839 --> 04:19.384
to a kind of mythology
of black criminality.

04:21.094 --> 04:24.431
<i>Go back and, you know, read the rhetoric
that people used then.</i>

04:25.390 --> 04:27.893
<i>They would say that the Negro
was out of control,</i>

04:27.976 --> 04:30.395
<i>that there's a threat of violence
to white women.</i>

04:32.230 --> 04:34.941
So the same sort of image
that we had of Uncle Remus

04:35.025 --> 04:37.652
<i>and these genial, kind of, black figures</i>

04:37.735 --> 04:44.159
was replaced by this rapacious,
uh, menacing, Negro male evil

04:44.242 --> 04:45.869
<i>that had to be banished.</i>

04:52.167 --> 04:53.836
Birth of a Nation <i>was</i>

04:53.919 --> 04:57.130
<i>just a profoundly important
cultural event.</i>

04:58.631 --> 05:00.550
<i>It's the first major blockbuster film,</i>

05:00.633 --> 05:04.805
hailed for both its artistic achievement
and for its political commentary.

05:04.888 --> 05:07.557
And when it was released,
it had this rapturous response.

05:07.641 --> 05:11.102
<i>You know, there were lines everywhere
that it was being shown.</i>

05:12.229 --> 05:15.148
<i>Birth of a Nation</i> confirmed the story

05:15.232 --> 05:19.777
that many whites wanted to tell
about the Civil War and its aftermath.

05:21.196 --> 05:25.200
<i>To erase defeat and to take out of it
sort of a martyrdom.</i>

05:27.410 --> 05:31.081
Woodrow Wilson, the sitting president,
had a private screening

05:31.164 --> 05:34.292
of it in the White House. He calls it,
"History written with lightning."

05:34.376 --> 05:36.544
And every image you see of a black person

05:36.628 --> 05:39.547
<i>is a demeaned, animal-like image.</i>

05:40.465 --> 05:42.259
<i>Cannibalistic, animalistic.</i>

05:43.551 --> 05:46.679
The image of the African American male.

05:48.181 --> 05:51.768
<i>There's a famous scene
where a woman throws herself off a cliff</i>

05:51.851 --> 05:55.688
<i>rather than be raped
by a black male criminal.</i>

05:56.231 --> 05:59.609
In the film, you see black people
being a threat to white women.

05:59.692 --> 06:04.907
All the myths of black men as rapists
was ultimately stemmed by the reality

06:04.990 --> 06:08.076
that the white political elite
and the business establishment

06:08.160 --> 06:09.369
needed black bodies working.

06:19.212 --> 06:21.965
<i>What we overlook</i>
<i>about</i> Birth of a Nation

06:22.049 --> 06:25.427
<i>is that it was also
a tremendously accurate prediction</i>

06:25.510 --> 06:28.346
of the way in which race
would operate in the United States.

06:40.943 --> 06:44.571
Birth of a Nation
<i>was almost directly responsible</i>

06:44.654 --> 06:46.198
for the rebirth of the Ku Klux Klan.

06:47.907 --> 06:53.288
<i>It had received this romantic,
glowing, heroic portrait.</i>

06:54.998 --> 06:58.376
<i>The Klan never had the ritual
of burning the cross.</i>

06:58.460 --> 07:00.628
<i>That was something
that D.W. Griffith came up with</i>

07:00.712 --> 07:03.006
<i>because he thought
that it was a great cinematic image.</i>

07:04.799 --> 07:07.761
<i>So it was literally
an instance of life imitating art.</i>

07:09.762 --> 07:11.431
The ripples emanate far out

07:11.514 --> 07:14.434
from just the simple fact
that it's a movie

07:14.517 --> 07:16.937
in the early motion picture age.

07:18.646 --> 07:21.649
<i>With the tremendous
burst of popularity</i>

07:21.733 --> 07:25.988
<i>that the Ku Klux Klan</i>
<i>had as a result of</i> Birth of a Nation

07:26.071 --> 07:28.781
came another wave of terrorism.

07:42.129 --> 07:45.298
<i>We had lynchings
between Reconstruction and World War II.</i>

07:45.382 --> 07:49.052
<i>Thousands of African Americans
murdered by mobs</i>

07:49.136 --> 07:52.180
under the idea
that they had done something criminal.

07:52.264 --> 07:55.600
<i>At the National Democratic
Convention in New York in 1924,</i>

07:55.683 --> 07:59.980
<i>it is estimated that at least
350 delegates were Klansmen.</i>

08:00.063 --> 08:03.941
<i>The demographic geography
of this country was shaped by that era.</i>

08:04.026 --> 08:05.943
<i>Now we have African Americans
in Los Angeles,</i>

08:06.028 --> 08:10.573
<i>in Oakland, and Chicago, and Cleveland,
Detroit, Boston, New York.</i>

08:10.657 --> 08:14.077
And very few people appreciate that
the African Americans in those communities

08:14.160 --> 08:18.248
did not go there as immigrants
looking for new economic opportunities.

08:18.331 --> 08:20.667
They went there as refugees from terror.

08:20.750 --> 08:24.129
We didn't just land in Oakland,
in LA, in Compton,

08:24.212 --> 08:27.590
in Harlem, in Brownsville in 2015.

08:27.674 --> 08:30.218
This is generational...
generational trauma.

08:30.301 --> 08:32.804
<i>The letters "KKK"
were carved with a penknife</i>

08:32.886 --> 08:35.765
<i>on the chest and stomach
of this man in Houston, Texas,</i>

08:35.847 --> 08:40.687
<i>after he had been hanged by his knees
from an oak tree and flogged with a chain.</i>

08:42.438 --> 08:45.650
<i>The Chicago Negro boy,
Emmett Till, is alleged</i>

08:45.733 --> 08:51.156
<i>to have paid unwelcome attention
to Roy Bryant's most attractive wife.</i>

09:02.792 --> 09:05.337
<i>And then
when it became unacceptable</i>

09:05.420 --> 09:07.922
<i>to engage in that kind of open terrorism,</i>

09:08.005 --> 09:10.133
then it shifted to something more legal.

09:10.217 --> 09:12.302
Segregation. Jim Crow.

09:13.928 --> 09:18.100
<i>Laws were passed
that relegated African Americans</i>

09:18.183 --> 09:21.061
to a permanent second-class status.

09:25.440 --> 09:30.278
These things really begin to live out
the prophecy that Griffith was making

09:30.362 --> 09:32.239
about the way that race operates.

09:32.322 --> 09:35.283
And this fear of crime
is central to all of this.

09:35.367 --> 09:37.577
Every time you saw a sign
that said "white and colored,"

09:37.660 --> 09:39.913
every time you had to deal
with the indignation

09:40.497 --> 09:42.499
of being told you can't go
through the front door.

09:42.582 --> 09:44.334
Every day you weren't allowed to vote,

09:44.417 --> 09:45.794
weren't allowed to go to school,

09:45.877 --> 09:48.755
you were bearing a burden
that was injurious.

09:52.342 --> 09:54.719
<i>Civil rights activists
began to see the necessity</i>

09:54.802 --> 09:57.180
of building not just
a civil rights movement,

09:57.264 --> 09:58.640
but a human rights movement.

09:58.723 --> 10:01.601
<i>And I think we should start now preparing</i>

10:01.684 --> 10:02.977
<i>for the inevitable.</i>

10:03.060 --> 10:04.146
<i>Yeah!</i>

10:04.229 --> 10:07.607
<i>And let us,
when that moment comes...</i>

10:09.401 --> 10:12.570
<i>go into the situations that we confront</i>

10:12.654 --> 10:18.576
<i>with a great deal of dignity,
sanity and reasonableness.</i>

10:26.251 --> 10:29.129
<i>They want to throw
white children and colored children</i>

10:29.212 --> 10:32.340
<i>into the melting pot of integration,</i>

10:32.424 --> 10:35.177
<i>through out of which
will come a conglomerated,</i>

10:35.260 --> 10:38.596
mulatto, mongrel class of people.

10:38.680 --> 10:41.308
Both races will be destroyed
in such a movement.

10:41.891 --> 10:45.061
<i>We just got a report here
on this end that the students are in.</i>

10:45.978 --> 10:48.981
<i>Negroes were trying
to integrate the bathing beaches.</i>

10:49.065 --> 10:52.527
<i>And the Florida Advisory Committee
to the US Civil Rights Commission</i>

10:52.610 --> 10:57.657
<i>warned that the city was becoming
a racial superbomb with a short fuse.</i>

10:59.492 --> 11:03.246
<i>Civil rights activists
began to be portrayed in the media</i>

11:03.329 --> 11:06.666
and among, you know,
many politicians as criminals.

11:06.749 --> 11:09.669
<i>People who are deliberately
violating the law,</i>

11:09.752 --> 11:12.297
<i>segregation laws
that existed in the South.</i>

11:14.799 --> 11:17.927
<i>For years now,
I have heard the word "wait."</i>

11:18.845 --> 11:23.975
<i>It rings in the ear of every Negro
with piercing familiarity.</i>

11:24.058 --> 11:28.396
<i>This wait has almost always meant never.</i>

11:29.939 --> 11:35.194
<i>Justice too long delayed
is justice denied.</i>

11:36.153 --> 11:39.241
I think that one of the most brilliant
tactics of the civil rights movement

11:39.324 --> 11:41.993
was its transformation
of the notion of criminality.

11:42.702 --> 11:45.747
Because for the first time,
being arrested was a noble thing.

11:47.624 --> 11:51.210
Being arrested by white people
was your worst nightmare.

11:51.294 --> 11:54.088
Still is, uh, for many African Americans.

11:54.171 --> 11:55.172
So what'd they do?

11:55.257 --> 11:59.051
They voluntarily defined a movement
around getting arrested.

11:59.135 --> 12:00.428
They turned it on its head.

12:04.432 --> 12:06.100
<i>If you looked at the history</i>

12:06.183 --> 12:09.103
<i>of black people's
various struggles in this country,</i>

12:09.186 --> 12:13.566
the connecting theme
is the attempt to be understood

12:13.650 --> 12:15.818
<i>as full, complicated human beings.</i>

12:18.446 --> 12:22.534
We are something other than
this, uh, visceral image of criminality

12:22.617 --> 12:26.162
<i>and menace and threat
to which people associate with us.</i>

12:36.047 --> 12:41.177
We're willing to be beaten for democracy,
and you misuse democracy in the street.

12:41.260 --> 12:44.597
Let us lay aside irrelevant differences...

12:45.932 --> 12:47.559
and make our nation whole.

12:51.354 --> 12:53.773
<i>The Civil Rights Act
and the Voting Rights Act said,</i>

12:53.856 --> 12:55.567
<i>"Finally, we admit it."</i>

12:55.650 --> 12:58.152
Though slavery ended in December 1865...

12:59.111 --> 13:03.115
"we took away these people's rights,
and now we're gonna fix it."

13:05.284 --> 13:06.661
<i>For the first time,</i>

13:06.744 --> 13:10.957
you know, promise of equal justice
becomes at least a possibility.

13:11.040 --> 13:14.794
Their cause must be our cause, too.

13:14.877 --> 13:16.754
<i>Unfortunately,
at the very same time</i>

13:16.838 --> 13:21.217
that the civil rights movement
was gaining steam,

13:21.300 --> 13:24.178
crime rates were beginning to rise
in this country.

13:24.261 --> 13:27.724
Crime was increasing
in the baby boom generation

13:27.807 --> 13:30.685
that had emerged
immediately after World War II.

13:30.768 --> 13:31.769
Now they were adults.

13:31.853 --> 13:37.734
So, just through sheer demographic change,
we had an increase in the amount of crime.

13:37.817 --> 13:41.363
And became very easy
for politicians then to say,

13:41.446 --> 13:47.910
um, that the civil rights movement itself
was contributing to rising crime rates,

13:47.994 --> 13:51.664
and that if we were to give
the Negroes their freedom, um,

13:51.748 --> 13:55.460
then we would be repaid,
as a nation, with crime.

13:57.294 --> 14:00.297
<i>The prison population
in the United States was largely flat</i>

14:00.382 --> 14:02.091
<i>throughout most of the 20th century.</i>

14:02.174 --> 14:04.511
<i>It didn't go up a lot.
It didn't come down a lot.</i>

14:04.594 --> 14:07.221
<i>But that changed in the 1970s.</i>

14:07.304 --> 14:09.682
And in the 1970s, we began an era

14:09.766 --> 14:13.895
which has been defined by this term,
"mass incarceration."

14:13.978 --> 14:18.065
This is a nation of laws,
and as Abraham Lincoln has said,

14:18.149 --> 14:21.528
"No one is above the law.
No one is below the law."

14:21.611 --> 14:23.446
And we're going to enforce the law

14:23.530 --> 14:27.241
and Americans should remember that,
if we're going to have law and order.

14:48.220 --> 14:53.393
<i>Each moment in history
is a fleeting time, precious and unique.</i>

14:53.476 --> 14:56.521
<i>But some stand out
as moments of beginning...</i>

14:57.480 --> 15:03.528
<i>in which courses are set
that shape decades or centuries.</i>

15:03.611 --> 15:06.113
<i>This can be such a moment.</i>

15:07.698 --> 15:12.829
It's with the Nixon era,
and the law and order period

15:12.912 --> 15:16.416
when crime begins to stand in for race.

15:16.499 --> 15:19.669
If there is one area
where the word "war" is appropriate,

15:19.752 --> 15:21.838
it is in the fight against crime.

15:21.921 --> 15:24.340
Part of what he talked about
was a war on crime.

15:24.424 --> 15:26.968
But that was one of those code words,

15:27.051 --> 15:29.471
what we might call
"dog-whistle politics" now,

15:29.554 --> 15:31.222
which really was referring to

15:31.305 --> 15:34.601
the black political movements of the day,
Black Power, Black Panthers,

15:34.684 --> 15:35.935
<i>the antiwar movement,</i>

15:36.018 --> 15:38.563
<i>the movements for women's
and gay liberation at that time,</i>

15:38.646 --> 15:41.608
which Nixon felt compelled
to fight back against.

15:41.691 --> 15:45.903
Once the federal government,
through the FBI, moves into an area,

15:45.987 --> 15:48.740
this should be warning
to those who engage in these acts

15:48.823 --> 15:52.494
<i>that they eventually
are going to be apprehended.</i>

15:52.577 --> 15:55.162
<i>There's this outcry
for law and order.</i>

15:55.997 --> 15:59.333
And Nixon becomes the person
who articulates that perfectly.

15:59.416 --> 16:03.254
<i>There can be no progress
in America without respect for law.</i>

16:03.337 --> 16:06.298
Many people felt like, uh,
we were losing control.

16:07.967 --> 16:11.596
<i>We need total war
in the United States</i>

16:11.679 --> 16:15.432
against the evils, uh,
that we see in our cities.

16:17.143 --> 16:20.897
<i>Federal spending
for local law enforcement will double.</i>

16:20.980 --> 16:22.439
<i>Time is running out
for the merchants</i>

16:22.524 --> 16:25.151
<i>of crime and corruption
in American society.</i>

16:26.318 --> 16:29.697
The wave of crime is not going to be
the wave of the future

16:29.781 --> 16:32.074
<i>in the United States of America.</i>

16:32.158 --> 16:34.994
We must wage
what I have called "total war"

16:35.077 --> 16:38.540
against public enemy number one
in the United States,

16:38.623 --> 16:39.957
the problem of dangerous drugs.

16:40.041 --> 16:41.626
"A war on drugs."

16:41.709 --> 16:46.172
And that utterance gave birth to this era,

16:46.255 --> 16:49.717
where we decided to deal
with drug addiction and drug dependency

16:49.801 --> 16:52.428
as a crime issue
rather than a health issue.

16:52.512 --> 16:54.681
Hundreds of thousands of people

16:54.764 --> 16:57.433
were sent to jails and prisons
for simple possession of marijuana,

16:57.517 --> 16:59.310
for low-level offenses.

17:00.978 --> 17:06.733
America's public enemy number one
in the United States is drug abuse.

17:07.694 --> 17:09.779
In order to fight and defeat this enemy,

17:09.862 --> 17:14.325
it is necessary to wage
a new, all-out offensive.

17:15.660 --> 17:19.288
This call for law and order
becomes integral to something that

17:19.371 --> 17:22.374
<i>comes to be known
as the Southern strategy.</i>

17:22.458 --> 17:26.753
<i>Nixon begins to recruit Southern whites,
formerly staunch Democrats,</i>

17:26.838 --> 17:29.215
<i>into the Republican fold.</i>

17:29.298 --> 17:31.300
<i>Persuading poor
and working-class whites</i>

17:31.383 --> 17:34.637
<i>to join the Republican Party in droves...</i>

17:34.721 --> 17:38.725
By speaking to,
in subtle and non-racist terms...

17:38.808 --> 17:41.143
a thinly veiled racial appeal...

17:41.227 --> 17:42.519
talking about crime,

17:42.604 --> 17:46.733
by talking about law and order
or the chaos of our urban cities

17:46.816 --> 17:48.484
unleashed by the civil rights movement.

17:48.568 --> 17:51.278
<i>We have launched
an all-out offensive against crime,</i>

17:51.362 --> 17:54.281
against narcotics,
against permissiveness in our country.

17:54.365 --> 17:57.034
<i>The rhetoric of
"get tough" and "law and order,"</i>

17:57.118 --> 18:02.164
<i>um, was part and parcel of the backlash
of the civil rights movement.</i>

18:03.332 --> 18:06.127
<i>A Nixon administration official
admitted the war on drugs</i>

18:06.210 --> 18:08.379
was all about
throwing black people in jail.

18:08.462 --> 18:09.463
<i>He said, quote,</i>

19:13.069 --> 19:15.697
Raise your right hand and repeat after me.

19:15.780 --> 19:18.407
I, Ronald Reagan, do solemnly swear...

19:18.490 --> 19:20.827
I, Ronald Reagan, do solemnly swear...

19:20.910 --> 19:23.537
that I will faithfully
execute the Office...

19:23.620 --> 19:28.876
The election of Ronald Reagan was, uh,
in many ways, transformative,

19:28.960 --> 19:30.837
in a negative sense.

19:30.920 --> 19:34.423
President Richard Nixon
was the first to coin the term

19:34.506 --> 19:35.842
"a war on drugs,"

19:35.925 --> 19:40.722
but President Ronald Reagan turned
that rhetorical war into a literal one.

19:40.805 --> 19:43.474
It's back to school time
for America's children.

19:43.557 --> 19:47.103
And while drug and alcohol abuse
cuts across all generations,

19:47.186 --> 19:49.521
it's especially damaging
to the young people

19:49.605 --> 19:51.315
<i>on whom our future depends.</i>

19:51.398 --> 19:56.403
The modern war on drugs was declared
by Ronald Reagan in 1982.

19:56.487 --> 19:59.115
As we mobilize for this national crusade,

19:59.198 --> 20:02.576
I'm mindful that drugs
are a constant temptation for millions.

20:02.660 --> 20:04.870
Popular opinion polls of the day

20:04.954 --> 20:07.915
show that it wasn't an issue
for most people in the United States.

20:07.999 --> 20:09.834
But Reagan was determined

20:09.917 --> 20:12.628
to put this onto the agenda
to define it as a problem.

20:12.712 --> 20:15.798
A war against drugs
is a war of individual battles.

20:15.882 --> 20:19.593
Reagan used his wife, for example,
in this "Just Say No" campaign.

20:19.676 --> 20:24.431
<i>She has helped so many of our young people
to say no to drugs.</i>

20:24.515 --> 20:26.934
<i>Nancy, much credit belongs to you.</i>

20:27.018 --> 20:28.310
This is your brain.

20:29.270 --> 20:30.897
This is drugs.

20:36.443 --> 20:38.195
This is your brain on drugs.

20:38.279 --> 20:39.446
I joined it.

20:39.530 --> 20:42.366
And some people said,
"Well, how can you join

20:42.449 --> 20:46.287
a person declaring a war on drugs,
someone like Ronald Reagan?"

20:46.370 --> 20:50.958
I joined with Nancy Reagan
because she said, "Just say no."

20:51.042 --> 20:55.254
Just say no so loud
that everyone around you can hear it.

20:55.337 --> 20:58.715
We're talking about a general education
that we're talking about.

20:58.800 --> 21:00.802
We're not talking about locking up people.

21:00.885 --> 21:05.306
We're talking about educating people.
We're talking about prevention.

21:05.389 --> 21:07.767
There was a crisis
in the US economy at that time.

21:07.850 --> 21:11.062
I regret to say
that we're in the worst economic mess

21:11.145 --> 21:12.729
<i>since the Great Depression.</i>

21:12.814 --> 21:14.982
There is a frontal assault

21:15.066 --> 21:19.195
on institutions that are designed
to assist human beings,

21:19.278 --> 21:23.950
<i>on the education system, welfare,
on jobs, healthcare.</i>

21:24.033 --> 21:27.829
Government programs that can't be paid for
out of a balanced budget

21:27.912 --> 21:30.331
must be paid for out of your pocket.

21:30.414 --> 21:33.459
<i>The rich are getting richer
and the poor are getting poorer.</i>

21:33.542 --> 21:37.171
The idea of expanding, uh,
the freedom of American business

21:37.254 --> 21:38.589
and the entrepreneurial class...

21:38.672 --> 21:43.219
We will save $1.8 billion
in fiscal year 1982.

21:43.302 --> 21:46.263
<i>Luxury stores like
Neiman Marcus predicts record sales.</i>

21:46.347 --> 21:49.225
<i>The number of Americans
dipping under the poverty level</i>

21:49.308 --> 21:51.685
<i>has reached the highest rate
in two decades.</i>

21:52.269 --> 21:55.898
Yes, there has been
an increase in poverty,

21:55.982 --> 21:59.526
but it is a lower rate of increase
than it was in the preceding years,

21:59.610 --> 22:00.777
before we got here.

22:00.862 --> 22:03.823
It has begun to decline,
but it is still going up.

22:03.906 --> 22:05.157
<i>In the mid-1980s,</i>

22:05.241 --> 22:08.494
we were already starting to embark
on a war on drugs

22:08.577 --> 22:11.956
and then all of a sudden,
along comes this new drug, crack cocaine.

22:12.039 --> 22:15.584
Steve Young reports
on a new kind of cocaine called crack.

22:15.667 --> 22:18.504
It's dangerous. It's deadly.
It will kill you.

22:18.587 --> 22:22.216
"The drug epidemic is as dangerous
as any terrorist that we face."

22:22.299 --> 22:25.302
<i>That is just some of what was said today
to House and Senate committees</i>

22:25.386 --> 22:27.179
<i>holding hearings on drug abuse in America.</i>

22:27.263 --> 22:30.933
<i>We have this drug that
could be marketed in very small doses,</i>

22:31.017 --> 22:32.977
relatively inexpensively,

22:33.060 --> 22:35.437
this was going to just
take over communities,

22:35.521 --> 22:38.232
and particularly
African American communities.

22:38.315 --> 22:42.153
Crack was largely an inner-city issue
and cocaine was largely a suburban issue.

22:42.236 --> 22:45.281
Smokable cocaine,
otherwise known as crack,

22:45.364 --> 22:47.574
<i>it is an uncontrolled fire.</i>

22:47.658 --> 22:50.202
<i>Congress,
in virtually record time,</i>

22:50.286 --> 22:54.039
established
mandatory sentencing penalties for crack

22:54.123 --> 22:57.584
that were far harsher than those
for powder cocaine.

22:57.668 --> 23:01.630
The same amount of time in prison
for one ounce of crack cocaine

23:01.713 --> 23:03.757
<i>that you get for 100 ounces
of powder cocaine.</i>

23:03.841 --> 23:06.552
<i>Police here are cracking down
on crack dealers.</i>

23:06.635 --> 23:13.559
Usually black or Hispanic, Latino,
they were getting long sentences

23:13.642 --> 23:15.102
for possession of crack.

23:15.185 --> 23:16.465
You're black with crack cocaine,

23:16.520 --> 23:19.148
you goin' to prison
for basically the rest of your life.

23:19.231 --> 23:22.609
Um, and if you're white, you're
pretty much getting slapped on the wrist.

23:22.693 --> 23:26.030
Cocaine... was more
sophisticated.

23:26.113 --> 23:27.990
It was just a powder.

23:28.074 --> 23:31.702
<i>By next year,
our spending for drug law enforcement</i>

23:31.785 --> 23:34.496
will have more than tripled
from its 1981 levels.

23:37.207 --> 23:41.587
All of a sudden, a scythe
went through our black communities,

23:42.129 --> 23:45.967
literally cutting off men
from their families,

23:46.050 --> 23:50.012
literally huge chunks
just disappearing into our prisons,

23:50.096 --> 23:52.514
and for really long times.

23:52.598 --> 23:54.516
<i>Millions of dollars
will be allocated</i>

23:55.351 --> 23:57.353
<i>for prison and jail facilities.</i>

23:57.436 --> 23:59.521
<i>These sorts of disparities
under Reagan</i>

23:59.605 --> 24:03.859
quickly exploded
into the era of mass incarceration.

24:03.942 --> 24:06.445
What Reagan ultimately does is...

24:06.528 --> 24:10.992
takes the problem of economic inequality,

24:11.075 --> 24:16.205
of hypersegregation in America's cities,
and the problem of drug abuse,

24:16.288 --> 24:21.210
and criminalizes all of that
in the form of the war on drugs.

24:21.293 --> 24:24.213
We absolutely should have treated
crack and cocaine,

24:24.296 --> 24:26.215
uh, as exactly the same thing.

24:26.298 --> 24:30.552
I think it was an enormous burden
on the black community,

24:30.636 --> 24:33.889
but it also fundamentally violated
a sense of core fairness.

24:33.972 --> 24:37.393
When crack cocaine hit
in the early '80s,

24:37.476 --> 24:40.562
there were a lot of mayors who felt
very strongly that this is a real threat

24:40.646 --> 24:41.981
and they wanted to crack down.

24:42.064 --> 24:45.234
And Rangel was one of the guys
pushing for stronger sentencing.

24:45.317 --> 24:48.445
It may have seemed
like a good idea at the time,

24:48.529 --> 24:51.240
but it sure didn't work out
as being effective.

24:51.323 --> 24:54.535
Then, years later,
there was an effort to rewrite history,

24:54.618 --> 25:00.374
that it was a racial disparity
put in by mean white people.

25:00.958 --> 25:02.501
Um, it's not where it came from.

25:02.584 --> 25:06.172
In many ways,
the so-called war on drugs

25:06.255 --> 25:09.091
was a war on communities of color,

25:09.175 --> 25:14.596
a war on black communities,
a war on Latino communities.

25:14.680 --> 25:18.600
And you see a rhetorical war that was,
you know,

25:18.684 --> 25:22.271
announced as part of a political strategy
by Richard Nixon

25:22.354 --> 25:26.233
and which morphed into a literal war
by Ronald Reagan,

25:26.317 --> 25:32.073
um, turning into something
that began to feel nearly genocidal

25:32.156 --> 25:34.700
in many poor communities of color.

25:34.783 --> 25:37.203
<i>So Nixon's Southern strategy</i>

25:37.286 --> 25:40.289
<i>was implemented right after
the civil rights movement.</i>

25:40.372 --> 25:41.707
<i>He played on fear of crime,</i>

25:41.790 --> 25:44.751
<i>and law and order
to win the election easily.</i>

25:46.337 --> 25:48.630
<i>Reagan promised tax cuts to the rich,</i>

25:48.714 --> 25:51.300
<i>and to throw all the crack users in jail,</i>

25:51.383 --> 25:53.969
<i>both of which devastated
communities of color</i>

25:54.053 --> 25:56.472
<i>but were effective
in getting the Southern vote.</i>

25:59.100 --> 26:03.354
There's really no understanding
of our American political culture

26:03.437 --> 26:05.189
without race at the center of it.

26:05.272 --> 26:08.901
<i>And in 1981,
just before Reagan assumed the presidency,</i>

26:08.984 --> 26:11.487
<i>his campaign strategist, Lee Atwater,</i>

26:11.570 --> 26:15.199
<i>was caught on tape
explaining the Southern strategy.</i>

26:15.282 --> 26:17.326
<i>In other words, you start out...</i>

27:30.607 --> 27:33.694
<i>The war on drugs had become
part of our popular culture,</i>

27:33.777 --> 27:35.362
<i>in television programs like</i> Cops.

27:38.156 --> 27:41.702
When you cut on your local news at night,
you see black men

27:41.785 --> 27:44.288
being paraded across the screen
in handcuffs.

27:45.747 --> 27:48.750
Black people, black men
and black people in general,

27:48.834 --> 27:53.755
<i>are overrepresented in news as criminals.</i>

27:53.839 --> 27:56.675
When I say overrepresented,
that means they are shown as criminals

27:56.758 --> 27:58.302
more times than is accurate,

27:58.385 --> 28:02.138
that they are actually criminals, right,
based on FBI statistics.

28:03.056 --> 28:06.768
I mean, I'm a big believer
in the power of media

28:06.852 --> 28:09.771
<i>full of these clichés
that basically present</i>

28:09.855 --> 28:12.816
<i>mostly black and brown folks
who seem like animals in cages,</i>

28:12.899 --> 28:16.069
and then someone
can turn off the TV thinking...

28:16.152 --> 28:17.488
"It's a good thing for prisons,

28:17.571 --> 28:20.366
because, otherwise, those crazy people
would be walking on my block."

28:20.449 --> 28:23.619
Creating a context
where people are afraid.

28:23.702 --> 28:25.537
And when you make people afraid,

28:25.621 --> 28:28.624
you can always justify
putting people in the garbage can.

28:28.707 --> 28:30.876
Chances are you could run into a kid

28:30.959 --> 28:33.629
waiting to relieve you
of your purse or wallet.

28:33.712 --> 28:36.340
Every media outlet in the country
thinks I'm less than human.

28:36.423 --> 28:41.177
I began to hear the word "super predator"
as if that was my name.

28:41.261 --> 28:42.512
Super predator.

28:42.596 --> 28:44.973
- <i>Super predator.</i>
- "Super predators," end quote.

28:45.056 --> 28:48.143
That's the word they used
to describe this generation,

28:48.227 --> 28:50.520
<i>and it was very, very effective.</i>

28:50.604 --> 28:52.356
Experts call them super predators.

28:52.439 --> 28:55.025
They are not just gangs of kids anymore.

28:55.108 --> 28:58.820
They are often the kinds of kids
that are called super predators.

28:58.904 --> 29:00.656
No conscience, no empathy.

29:00.739 --> 29:02.491
<i>A group of kids growing up</i>

29:02.574 --> 29:05.201
<i>essentially fatherless,
godless and jobless.</i>

29:05.285 --> 29:06.411
For me, what's disturbing

29:06.495 --> 29:08.747
is the degree to which black people
bought into that.

29:08.830 --> 29:12.167
Animals, beasts that needed
to be controlled.

29:12.960 --> 29:15.337
When those grandmothers say,
"But he's a good boy.

29:16.422 --> 29:19.215
He never did anything,"
don't you believe it.

29:19.299 --> 29:20.842
<i>Black communities began</i>

29:20.926 --> 29:24.430
to actually support policies
that criminalized their own children.

29:24.513 --> 29:27.223
<i>Last night, the eight teens
accused of the attack</i>

29:27.308 --> 29:30.143
<i>were arraigned on charges of rape
and attempted murder.</i>

29:30.227 --> 29:34.564
<i>In the Central Park jogger case,
they put five innocent teens in prison,</i>

29:34.648 --> 29:35.899
<i>because the public pressure</i>

29:35.983 --> 29:38.777
<i>to lock up these quote, unquote animals
was so strong.</i>

29:38.860 --> 29:41.447
You better believe
that I hate the people

29:41.530 --> 29:44.366
that took this girl
and raped her brutally.

29:44.449 --> 29:46.827
- You better believe it.
<i>- Donald Trump wanted to give</i>

29:46.910 --> 29:48.370
<i>these kids the death penalty,</i>

29:48.454 --> 29:51.332
<i>and he took out a full page ad
to put the pressure on.</i>

29:52.082 --> 29:55.043
<i>These children, four of them under 18,</i>

29:55.126 --> 29:58.297
<i>all went to adult prisons
for six to eleven years,</i>

29:58.380 --> 30:02.050
<i>before DNA evidence proved
they were all innocent.</i>

30:02.133 --> 30:04.553
We make them their crime.
That's how we introduced them.

30:04.636 --> 30:06.116
"That's a rapist. That's a murderer."

30:06.179 --> 30:08.223
That's a robber.
That's a sex offender.

30:08.307 --> 30:10.559
"That's a burglar.
That's a gang leader."

30:10.642 --> 30:13.895
And through that lens,
it becomes so much easier

30:13.979 --> 30:16.857
to accept that they're guilty
and that they should go to prison.

30:18.400 --> 30:23.989
The objective reality is...
that virtually no one who is white

30:24.656 --> 30:29.453
understands the challenge
of being black in America.

30:29.953 --> 30:36.543
So you have then educated a public,
deliberately, over years, over decades,

30:36.627 --> 30:42.132
to believe that black men in particular,
and black people in general,

30:42.215 --> 30:43.759
are criminals.

30:43.842 --> 30:45.010
I want to be clear,

30:45.093 --> 30:47.693
because I'm not just saying
that white people believe this, right?

30:47.763 --> 30:53.477
Black people also believe this
and are terrified of our own selves.

30:54.061 --> 30:56.855
You want to go back to the days
of military weakness,

30:56.938 --> 30:59.107
caring more about criminals than victims?

30:59.190 --> 31:02.110
We can't risk that.
I'd like your vote on Tuesday.

31:02.194 --> 31:05.572
<i>Leadership that's on your side.
Michael Dukakis for president.</i>

31:05.656 --> 31:07.949
In the midst of the, uh,
presidential campaign,

31:08.033 --> 31:12.954
an ad was released about a person
by the name of Willie Horton.

31:13.038 --> 31:15.749
<i>Bush and Dukakis on crime.</i>

31:15.832 --> 31:18.209
<i>Dukakis not only
opposes the death penalty,</i>

31:18.293 --> 31:21.797
<i>he allowed first degree murderers
to have weekend passes from prison.</i>

31:21.880 --> 31:23.173
<i>One was Willie Horton.</i>

31:23.256 --> 31:28.303
This became a focal point
of an entire presidential campaign.

31:28.387 --> 31:30.514
<i>Horton fled,
kidnapped a young couple,</i>

31:30.597 --> 31:33.224
<i>stabbing the man
and repeatedly raping his girlfriend.</i>

31:33.308 --> 31:36.853
<i>Weekend prison passes.
Dukakis on crime.</i>

31:36.937 --> 31:40.774
Dukakis had protected the program,
vetoed an effort to repeal it,

31:40.857 --> 31:43.985
in that he favored letting murderers
out on the weekend.

31:44.069 --> 31:46.738
<i>That Dukakis
had a double-digit lead over Bush</i>

31:46.822 --> 31:50.451
before the campaign
focused on Willie Horton,

31:50.534 --> 31:54.079
and after that, Bush overtook Dukakis
and won the election.

31:54.162 --> 31:58.083
<i>Which candidate for president
can you count on to be tough on crime?</i>

31:58.166 --> 31:59.668
<i>George Bush.</i>

31:59.751 --> 32:04.548
Bush won the election by creating fear
around black men as criminal,

32:04.631 --> 32:07.092
without saying that's what he was doing.

32:07.175 --> 32:10.345
A very racially, um...

32:10.429 --> 32:13.765
you know, divisive moment.

32:13.849 --> 32:16.477
Depicting an African American criminal,
I think, was deliberate

32:16.560 --> 32:18.311
on the part of that campaign.

32:18.394 --> 32:20.105
There's no one who can tell me otherwise.

32:20.188 --> 32:23.942
Liberals call him Willie Horton to make it
sound like you're being dismissive.

32:24.443 --> 32:28.655
Original article was <i>Reader's Digest.</i>
William Horton, no picture.

32:28.738 --> 32:30.699
The Democrats want you to know
he's black.

32:31.658 --> 32:32.826
Thanks, Grover.

32:35.161 --> 32:37.080
It was not his name,

32:37.163 --> 32:40.709
it was his image
that was sensationalized.

32:40.792 --> 32:44.546
Liberals that announced that it was mean
to pick on a murderer and a rapist

32:44.630 --> 32:47.799
lose all credibility on this discussion.
They just lose it.

32:47.883 --> 32:48.967
And people go,

32:49.050 --> 32:51.650
"We don't want to hear anything else
you have to say about crime."

32:51.720 --> 32:54.139
No matter what anybody says
or what anybody does,

32:54.222 --> 32:59.227
they know exactly what button
they were trying to hit with that ad.

32:59.311 --> 33:01.563
<i>Stabbing the man
and raping his girlfriend.</i>

33:01.647 --> 33:07.861
It went to a kind of primitive fear,
a primitive American fear,

33:07.944 --> 33:13.158
because Willie Horton
was metaphorically the black male rapist

33:13.241 --> 33:16.119
<i>that had been a staple
of the white imagination</i>

33:16.202 --> 33:18.246
<i>since the time just after slavery.</i>

33:20.874 --> 33:24.252
<i>Here was a black man
convicted of rape.</i>

33:25.045 --> 33:28.882
<i>"I will be the savior and protector
of the white population."</i>

33:28.965 --> 33:35.305
Never minding the fact that the history
of interracial rape in this country,

33:35.388 --> 33:41.352
that that record is far more marked
by white rape against black women

33:41.436 --> 33:43.772
than of black men against white women.

33:55.075 --> 33:56.159
Patsey.

34:00.330 --> 34:05.126
<i>This idea
that had such great artistic utility</i>

34:05.210 --> 34:07.629
<i>in 1915 in</i> Birth of a Nation

34:07.713 --> 34:10.215
<i>still had a great deal
of political utility</i>

34:10.297 --> 34:11.842
almost at the end of that century.

34:11.925 --> 34:18.098
The way that we appeal to voters'
sense of fear and anxiety in our nation

34:18.181 --> 34:20.350
runs through black bodies.

35:03.935 --> 35:07.230
<i>A new generation
of Democrats, Bill Clinton and Al Gore.</i>

35:07.314 --> 35:09.441
<i>They don't think the way
the old Democratic party did.</i>

35:09.524 --> 35:13.153
<i>They've sent a strong signal to criminals
by supporting the death penalty.</i>

35:13.236 --> 35:18.574
Looking at the way in which
Democrats were defeated in 1988,

35:18.659 --> 35:21.995
<i>or they were defeated in 1984,
or they were defeated in 1980,</i>

35:22.078 --> 35:24.497
there comes to be a sentiment
among the Democrats

35:24.580 --> 35:29.044
that they have to adopt a position
that is much more, uh, kind of, centrist.

35:29.127 --> 35:30.879
It became virtually impossible

35:30.962 --> 35:34.549
for a politician to run
and appear soft on crime.

35:34.633 --> 35:37.343
I was not for the bill
that he was talking about

35:37.427 --> 35:39.554
because it was not tough enough
on the criminal.

35:39.638 --> 35:42.432
<i>In an environment
where everybody's doing the same thing,</i>

35:42.515 --> 35:44.434
<i>everybody's competing
to be tough on crime,</i>

35:44.517 --> 35:46.728
you quickly all end up in the same space,

35:46.812 --> 35:49.690
so it doesn't become a political advantage
unless you do something more.

35:49.773 --> 35:52.025
We need more police on the street.

35:52.108 --> 35:54.628
There is a crime bill which would
put more police on the street,

35:54.694 --> 35:57.447
which was killed for this session
by a filibuster in the Senate,

35:57.530 --> 35:59.825
mostly by Republican senators.

35:59.908 --> 36:03.578
We'd consistently had,
"Squishy, soft liberal won't protect you.

36:03.662 --> 36:06.873
Tough, conservative will protect you."
And we won that fight every time.

36:06.957 --> 36:09.876
And by the late '80s, early '90s,
people like Bill Clinton

36:09.960 --> 36:12.921
had begun to figure out
they had to be able to match us.

36:13.004 --> 36:17.718
I will faithfully execute the Office
of President of the United States.

36:17.801 --> 36:20.971
Bill Clinton is trying to figure out

36:21.054 --> 36:25.475
how he can deal with a country
that's still basically Reagan's country,

36:25.558 --> 36:28.186
but he's trying to govern as a Democrat.

36:28.269 --> 36:33.108
Violent crime and the fear it provokes
are crippling our society.

36:33.191 --> 36:37.653
Then some high-profile,
very horrendous crimes take place.

36:37.738 --> 36:41.700
Residents pull together
in the search for 12-year-old Polly Klaas.

36:41.783 --> 36:44.619
They are now coping with the discovery
of her body over the weekend.

36:44.703 --> 36:50.125
<i>Polly Klaas, abducted from
her bedroom at home and ultimately killed,</i>

36:50.208 --> 36:53.837
which led to the California
"three strikes and you're out" law.

36:53.920 --> 36:56.089
When you commit a third violent crime,

36:56.172 --> 36:58.967
you will be put away
and put away for good.

36:59.050 --> 37:01.552
Three strikes and you are out.

37:01.636 --> 37:03.679
A person's convicted
of their third felony,

37:03.764 --> 37:07.475
<i>essentially that person is mandated
to prison for the rest of their lives.</i>

37:07.558 --> 37:10.353
<i>So many third-strike defendants
awaiting trial,</i>

37:10.436 --> 37:12.063
<i>the Los Angeles Sheriff's Department</i>

37:12.147 --> 37:16.359
<i>is forced to release 4,200
misdemeanor inmates every month</i>

37:16.442 --> 37:19.570
<i>to make room for incoming
three-strike prisoners.</i>

37:19.654 --> 37:21.823
It's in line with many other policies
we've created,

37:21.907 --> 37:23.616
<i>particularly mandatory minimums.</i>

37:23.699 --> 37:27.453
"Mandatory sentencing." We said
we were no longer going to let judges

37:27.537 --> 37:29.831
consider the circumstances around a crime.

37:29.915 --> 37:32.250
We're just going to impose
a mandatory sentence.

37:32.333 --> 37:33.893
And that's a difficult thing for judges

37:33.919 --> 37:37.756
because they are trying
to dispense justice on a daily basis

37:37.839 --> 37:39.715
and are unable to do so.

37:39.800 --> 37:44.262
<i>In many California communities,
all civil trials have been canceled</i>

37:44.345 --> 37:46.222
<i>to catch up
with the criminal case workload.</i>

37:46.306 --> 37:49.184
<i>We've taken discretion
away from judges,</i>

37:49.267 --> 37:51.394
arguably the most neutral party
in the court,

37:51.477 --> 37:53.897
and given it over to prosecutors.

37:53.980 --> 38:00.737
Ninety-five percent of elected prosecutors
throughout the United States are white.

38:00.821 --> 38:04.950
Serious, violent criminals
serve at least 85% of their sentence.

38:05.033 --> 38:07.786
<i>We passed Truth in Sentencing
that kept people imprisoned</i>

38:07.869 --> 38:09.204
<i>for 85% of their sentence.</i>

38:09.287 --> 38:12.665
<i>Truth in Sentencing.
You're sentenced to an amount of time.</i>

38:12.748 --> 38:14.125
<i>The public wants to be confident</i>

38:14.209 --> 38:17.087
<i>that you're gonna do
just about every bit of that time.</i>

38:17.170 --> 38:19.005
We've done away with parole.

38:19.089 --> 38:24.177
So, in the federal system, when you get
20 years or 30 years, that's what you got.

38:24.260 --> 38:25.929
We had parole in this country

38:26.012 --> 38:29.057
as a mechanism for getting people
out of jails and prisons

38:29.140 --> 38:31.860
when it was clear that they were
no longer a threat to public safety.

38:31.935 --> 38:35.521
Sharanda has spent the last 16 years
in prison, and she'll die there,

38:35.605 --> 38:37.899
because she was sentenced
to life without parole.

38:37.983 --> 38:39.985
Her only crime?
Transporting cocaine.

38:40.068 --> 38:42.904
And when I say "only crime,"
I mean only crime.

38:42.988 --> 38:44.739
She had no other arrests. None.

38:44.823 --> 38:50.703
The judge was required...
required to send Sharanda away for life.

38:50.787 --> 38:53.832
<i>Longer sentences,
three strikes and you're out,</i>

38:54.332 --> 38:58.419
almost 60
new capital punishment offenses...

38:58.503 --> 39:00.588
<i>And then comes the Congress</i>

39:00.671 --> 39:06.344
with a proposal for a $30 billion
federal crime bill of 1994

39:06.427 --> 39:10.515
that was heavily loaded towards
law enforcement incarceration.

39:10.598 --> 39:13.935
I propose a 21st century crime bill

39:14.018 --> 39:16.354
to deploy
the latest technologies and tactics

39:16.437 --> 39:19.190
<i>to make our communities even safer.</i>

39:19.274 --> 39:21.276
That omnibus crime bill was responsible

39:21.359 --> 39:24.779
for a massive expansion
of the prison system.

39:24.863 --> 39:29.450
<i>And beyond that, it provided all kinds
of money and perverse incentives</i>

39:29.534 --> 39:31.953
for law enforcement
to do a lot of the things

39:32.037 --> 39:34.164
that we nowadays consider to be abusive.

39:34.247 --> 39:39.044
It will be used to build prisons to keep
100,000 violent criminals off the street.

39:39.127 --> 39:42.713
<i>Not only does he increase
funding to states to build prisons</i>

39:42.797 --> 39:46.301
<i>to lock up as many people
involved in drug crimes,</i>

39:46.384 --> 39:49.804
but also to put
100,000 police officers on the street.

39:49.888 --> 39:55.726
Crime has been a hot political issue
used too often to divide us.

39:55.810 --> 39:58.438
What President Clinton did in 1994

39:58.521 --> 40:02.317
is actually far more harmful
than his predecessors

40:02.400 --> 40:05.111
because he actually built
that infrastructure that we see today,

40:05.195 --> 40:10.951
the militarization all the way down
to small, rural police departments

40:11.034 --> 40:13.078
that have SWAT teams.

40:13.161 --> 40:15.163
<i>And again we see
this kind of notching up</i>

40:15.246 --> 40:18.416
<i>of the number of people who were
being arrested at every level</i>

40:18.499 --> 40:22.712
<i>and this kind
of exploding prison population.</i>

40:24.672 --> 40:26.882
<i>We are a nation
that professes freedom,</i>

40:26.967 --> 40:31.137
yet we have this mass incarceration,
this hyperincarceration,

40:31.221 --> 40:35.016
uh, that is trawling into it,
grinding into it,

40:35.100 --> 40:37.102
our most vulnerable citizenry,

40:37.185 --> 40:40.271
and is overwhelmingly biased
towards people of color.

40:51.992 --> 40:54.077
<i>But I want to say
a few words about it.</i>

40:56.955 --> 41:00.124
Because I signed a bill
that made the problem worse.

41:00.625 --> 41:02.418
And I want to admit it.

41:02.502 --> 41:06.922
His 1994 crime bill, something
that he now admits was a mistake...

41:07.007 --> 41:08.799
There were longer sentences.

41:10.843 --> 41:15.140
And most of these people
are in prison under state law,

41:15.223 --> 41:18.226
but the federal law set a trend.

41:20.353 --> 41:22.647
And that was overdone.
We were wrong about that.

41:22.730 --> 41:27.902
Well, I think it's important
that President Clinton, um, acknowledges

41:27.986 --> 41:34.700
that things didn't turn out exactly
as he and all of us would've wished.

41:34.784 --> 41:38.579
I'm happy that he realizes
the error of his ways.

41:38.663 --> 41:41.791
I think he knew back then that
it wasn't good policy, I'll be honest.

41:41.874 --> 41:46.004
Back then, there was an outcry
over the rising crime rate.

41:46.087 --> 41:50.091
And people from all communities
were asking that action be taken.

41:50.175 --> 41:54.095
Now, my husband said
at the NAACP last summer

41:54.179 --> 41:57.932
that it solved some problems,
but it created other problems,

41:58.016 --> 41:59.100
and I agree.

41:59.184 --> 42:02.353
I'm glad to see that he is apologetic,

42:02.437 --> 42:06.024
but I think he has to take responsibility
and accountability for that,

42:06.107 --> 42:07.317
and so does Hillary,

42:07.400 --> 42:10.445
because she supported it,
then and up until recently.

42:10.528 --> 42:14.990
<i>Bill Clinton faced off against
a group of Black Lives Matter protestors</i>

42:15.075 --> 42:17.577
<i>protesting a 1994 crime bill</i>

42:17.660 --> 42:21.247
<i>that they say led to a surge
in the imprisonment of black people.</i>

42:21.330 --> 42:24.083
I don't know how you would characterize

42:24.167 --> 42:28.963
the gang leaders who got
13-year-old kids hopped up on crack

42:29.047 --> 42:34.260
and sent 'em out onto the street
to murder other African American children.

42:34.344 --> 42:37.888
Maybe you thought they were good citizens.
She didn't.

42:37.972 --> 42:39.599
She didn't!

42:39.682 --> 42:44.437
You are defending the people
who kill the lives you say matter.

42:44.520 --> 42:45.855
<i>Tell the truth.</i>

42:46.356 --> 42:48.858
We can't ignore the reality of force here.

42:48.941 --> 42:52.112
The policies
that Bill Clinton put forward,

42:52.195 --> 42:54.739
you know, mandatory minimums,
three strikes...

42:54.822 --> 42:57.242
Those were a use of political force.

42:57.325 --> 42:59.160
They forced millions of people,

42:59.244 --> 43:02.413
who would not otherwise
be in prison today, into prison.

43:02.497 --> 43:04.374
They forced families to be broken.

43:04.457 --> 43:06.834
They forced children
to live without their parents.

43:06.917 --> 43:07.960
That's what happened.

43:15.301 --> 43:16.385
<i>Why?</i>

43:18.429 --> 43:21.766
We shouldn't ask,
"Why is Bill Clinton so strong?"

43:21.849 --> 43:24.394
We should ask,
"Why is the black community so weak

43:24.477 --> 43:26.521
in our inability to defend ourselves?"

43:26.604 --> 43:31.192
Let's not forget how many martyrs
we put in the ground in the '60s and '70s.

43:31.276 --> 43:35.863
Let's not forget how many of our leaders
had to leave the country or are in prison.

43:35.946 --> 43:40.034
You stripped out
a whole generation of leadership.

43:40.118 --> 43:42.828
You ran them out the country,
you put them in prison,

43:42.912 --> 43:45.540
you put them in... in cemeteries.

43:45.623 --> 43:48.083
And then you unleash this blitzkrieg,

43:48.168 --> 43:50.753
and we don't have the ability
to defend ourselves.

43:50.836 --> 43:56.884
You can tell the story
of white leadership in America

43:56.967 --> 43:59.011
and never mention the FBI one time.

43:59.095 --> 44:03.057
You can't tell the story
of black leadership, not one,

44:03.433 --> 44:06.561
without having to deal
with the full weight

44:06.644 --> 44:09.689
of the criminal justice system
weaponizing its black dissent.

44:09.772 --> 44:13.484
I'm tired of living every day
under the threat of death.

44:13.568 --> 44:15.570
I have no martyr complex.

44:15.653 --> 44:19.407
I want to live as long
as anybody in this building tonight.

44:19.490 --> 44:23.953
<i>Dr. King, people forget,
was not this beloved figure</i>

44:24.036 --> 44:25.996
<i>that everybody wants to put on a pedestal.</i>

44:26.080 --> 44:29.417
<i>Uh, he was considered one
of the most dangerous people in America</i>

44:29.500 --> 44:32.462
<i>by the head
of the Federal Bureau of Investigations.</i>

44:34.172 --> 44:36.632
Don't tell me
that Dr. King has no relevance

44:36.716 --> 44:38.009
to young brothers in the street.

44:38.092 --> 44:40.720
They dealing with little cops.
He was dealing with the top cop.

44:40.803 --> 44:43.764
We were brought here
against our will.

44:43.848 --> 44:46.934
We were not brought here
to be made citizens.

44:47.017 --> 44:52.482
We were not brought here
to enjoy the, uh, constitutional gifts

44:52.565 --> 44:54.567
that they speak so beautifully about.

44:54.650 --> 44:58.738
<i>Malcolm's whole entourage
was infiltrated with police.</i>

44:58.821 --> 45:00.573
<i>He may have had as many police</i>

45:00.656 --> 45:03.493
as he had regular folk
in his entourage, under cover.

45:03.576 --> 45:05.245
So afraid of black dissent.

45:05.328 --> 45:08.289
FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover
today asserted that the Black Panthers

45:08.373 --> 45:10.750
represent the greatest internal threat
to the nation.

45:11.292 --> 45:12.793
<i>J. Edgar Hoover said</i>

45:12.877 --> 45:17.047
<i>these Panthers represent
the greatest threat</i>

45:17.131 --> 45:19.467
to American democracy at the time.

45:20.885 --> 45:23.846
<i>The Panthers never were that big.</i>

45:23.929 --> 45:26.766
I mean, no one in their right mind
could ever believe

45:26.849 --> 45:29.560
that the Black Panthers
were gonna bring down

45:29.644 --> 45:33.648
the greatest military force
in the history of the world.

45:33.731 --> 45:35.983
The whole movement was criminalized

45:36.066 --> 45:39.236
and destroyed systematically
by the government.

45:39.320 --> 45:41.989
People haven't thought about
what it means to lose a Fred Hampton,

45:42.072 --> 45:45.576
<i>who somehow was able to pull together
blacks and whites</i>

45:45.660 --> 45:48.120
<i>and Puerto Ricans and Native Americans</i>

45:48.203 --> 45:50.831
to fight for justice at 21.

45:50.915 --> 45:53.501
We're going to say it after this
and after I'm locked up

45:53.584 --> 45:55.085
and after everybody's locked up,

45:55.169 --> 45:58.798
that you can jail revolutionaries,
but you can't jail a revolution.

45:58.881 --> 46:00.341
He had to go.

46:00.425 --> 46:05.596
The head of the Black Panthers in Illinois
was killed today by police in Chicago.

46:05.680 --> 46:08.641
<i>Illinois Panther Chairman
Fred Hampton and another Panther leader</i>

46:08.724 --> 46:11.101
<i>from Peoria, Illinois, were killed.</i>

46:11.185 --> 46:13.980
This is where our chairman
had his brains blown out

46:14.063 --> 46:17.900
as he lay in his bed
sleeping at 4:30 in the morning.

46:17.983 --> 46:21.571
<i>They literally went
and shot his whole house up,</i>

46:21.654 --> 46:24.532
<i>with his pregnant wife
next to him in the bed.</i>

46:25.408 --> 46:29.870
So afraid of a leader
that could unite people.

46:29.954 --> 46:31.872
We know the history of folks

46:31.956 --> 46:34.834
who've done this kind of standing up
to these systems,

46:34.917 --> 46:37.545
and we know how the system has
murdered them, assassinated them,

46:37.628 --> 46:42.007
exiled them, excluded them,
or found ways to discredit them.

46:43.551 --> 46:46.554
Assata Shakur was one of the great leaders
of the Black Liberation Army.

46:46.637 --> 46:50.641
That, um, order given by J. Edgar Hoover

46:50.725 --> 46:56.856
was essentially
to destroy any black, progressive...

46:58.190 --> 47:00.568
Third World movement in this country.

47:00.651 --> 47:02.069
<i>They put her in prison,</i>

47:02.152 --> 47:05.280
and her allies said,
"We're not gonna leave her in prison."

47:05.364 --> 47:07.764
Her white allies said,
"We're not gonna leave her in prison."

47:07.825 --> 47:10.745
<i>And pulled her out of prison and got her
to Cuba. She's in Cuba right now.</i>

47:10.786 --> 47:13.748
<i>And within the next five years,</i>

47:13.831 --> 47:19.462
something like, uh, 300 prisons
are in the planning stages.

47:19.545 --> 47:20.921
This government has the intentions

47:21.005 --> 47:24.008
of throwing more and more people
in prison.

47:25.175 --> 47:27.970
<i>Criminalization of Assata Shakur,</i>

47:28.053 --> 47:33.976
the use of the media to represent her
as a dangerous criminal.

47:34.059 --> 47:36.604
And of course, in my own case,

47:36.687 --> 47:42.109
where I was represented by the FBI
as being armed and dangerous.

47:42.192 --> 47:44.945
The FBI has put
black militant Angela Davis

47:45.029 --> 47:47.448
on its list
of the Ten Most Wanted Fugitives.

47:47.532 --> 47:51.452
<i>Then with Angela Davis,
the power of the black intellect...</i>

47:51.535 --> 47:53.454
<i>One thing
that we have to talk about,</i>

47:53.538 --> 47:56.707
coming to grips with,
is this whole question of crime.

47:56.791 --> 48:00.210
What does it mean
to be a criminal in this society?

48:00.294 --> 48:01.671
That had to be broken up.

48:01.754 --> 48:05.466
<i>And in my case, Ronald Reagan
was the governor of California,</i>

48:05.550 --> 48:07.802
<i>Richard Nixon was
the president of the US.</i>

48:07.885 --> 48:12.473
<i>The whole apparatus of the state
was set up against me,</i>

48:12.557 --> 48:16.644
<i>and they really meant to send me
to the death chamber</i>

48:16.727 --> 48:18.395
<i>in order to make a point.</i>

48:18.479 --> 48:21.649
The actions of the FBI
in apprehending Angela Davis,

48:21.732 --> 48:25.319
a rather remarkable, uh, story again...

48:25.402 --> 48:28.072
<i>The system tried
to put the sister on trial,</i>

48:28.155 --> 48:30.908
and the sister said,
"No, we puttin' you on trial."

48:34.244 --> 48:36.664
Comes in, the big Afro,
she didn't go press her hair.

48:36.747 --> 48:38.541
<i>She was facing major time.</i>

48:38.624 --> 48:41.085
You know, most people,
they'd have got a nice little press.

48:41.168 --> 48:44.004
You know? They'd have been
in there with little white gloves on,

48:44.088 --> 48:45.923
praying to Jesus.
She came in like this.

48:46.841 --> 48:51.261
And she devastated the prosecution
and walked out of there free.

48:53.973 --> 48:56.058
<i>But the question is
how do you get there?</i>

48:56.141 --> 48:58.769
Do you get there
by confrontation, violence?

48:58.853 --> 49:00.563
Oh, was that the question you were asking?

