56:57.081 --> 57:00.917
<i>After the outcry over Stand Your Ground
and the Trayvon Martin tragedy...</i>

57:01.001 --> 57:04.421
Wal-Mart stepped out of ALEC.
It left ALEC, abandoned ALEC.

57:04.504 --> 57:06.965
But the Wal-Mart family
continues to fund ALEC.

57:07.049 --> 57:10.219
<i>Other corporations
followed suit and stepped away from ALEC,</i>

57:10.302 --> 57:13.597
<i>but many corporations
are still members, including...</i>

57:13.680 --> 57:16.141
<i>Koch Industries,
State Farm Insurance,</i>

57:16.225 --> 57:19.269
PhRMA, which is the lobbying group
for the pharmaceutical industry.

57:19.353 --> 57:21.855
ALEC has been supported
by the tobacco industry

57:21.939 --> 57:23.773
<i>as well as AT&T and Verizon.</i>

57:23.857 --> 57:25.692
<i>And for nearly two decades,</i>

57:25.776 --> 57:28.195
one corporation was
Corrections Corporation of America.

57:28.778 --> 57:31.531
<i>Every day,
we serve our communities.</i>

57:31.615 --> 57:33.325
<i>From small towns to large cities,</i>

57:33.408 --> 57:36.495
<i>at more than 60 locations
across our country.</i>

57:36.578 --> 57:39.248
<i>As the nation's fifth largest
correctional system,</i>

57:39.331 --> 57:43.793
<i>we build, own and manage
secure correctional facilities.</i>

57:43.877 --> 57:46.380
<i>CCA was the first
private prison corporation in the US.</i>

57:46.463 --> 57:49.341
<i>It started as a small company,
in Tennessee, in 1983.</i>

57:50.425 --> 57:52.636
These folks started
making contracts with states.

57:52.719 --> 57:54.554
And they had to protect their investments,

57:54.638 --> 57:58.225
so the states were required
to keep these prisons filled

57:58.308 --> 57:59.828
<i>even if nobody was committing a crime.</i>

58:00.394 --> 58:03.981
<i>And in the late '80s and early '90s,
this became a growth industry</i>

58:04.064 --> 58:07.317
unlike very few growth industries
in America's history.

58:07.401 --> 58:12.197
Uh, it was absolutely
a model guaranteed to succeed.

58:13.698 --> 58:18.745
<i>And one of the ways we see that
is through the role of CCA within ALEC</i>

58:18.828 --> 58:20.705
to advance a series of bills.

58:20.789 --> 58:22.791
All the legislation you could think of

58:22.874 --> 58:26.628
that we fight so hard against,
"three strikes, you're out..."

58:26.711 --> 58:28.963
Three strikes and you are out.

58:29.048 --> 58:30.715
Mandatory minimum sentencing laws...

58:30.799 --> 58:33.302
serve at least 85% of their sentence.

58:33.385 --> 58:35.554
Were the ones
they were putting out there

58:35.637 --> 58:39.599
like on a premiere
pre-fixed dinner menu,

58:39.683 --> 58:44.229
<i>a steady influx of bodies
to generate the profit</i>

58:44.313 --> 58:46.481
that would go to the shareholders.

58:47.691 --> 58:51.236
<i>Through ALEC,
CCA became the leader in private prisons.</i>

58:51.945 --> 58:56.658
<i>It's a multibillion-dollar business today
that gets rich off punishment.</i>

58:56.741 --> 58:59.661
<i>We are America's leader
in partnership corrections.</i>

58:59.744 --> 59:01.080
<i>We are CCA.</i>

59:01.163 --> 59:02.622
<i>And so, through ALEC,</i>

59:02.706 --> 59:06.293
CCA had a hand in shaping crime policy
across the country,

59:06.376 --> 59:11.173
including, not just prison privatization,
but the rapid increase in criminalization.

59:11.757 --> 59:15.927
I think this accusation, you know,
quite frankly, is just false.

59:16.010 --> 59:21.641
That somehow ALEC was in favor
of imprisoning a bunch of people, uh,

59:21.725 --> 59:23.435
because of private prisons...

59:23.518 --> 59:28.148
I think that's just, unfortunately,
one of these tactics they do on ALEC.

59:28.232 --> 59:32.152
ALEC pushed forward a number of policies
to increase the number of people in prison

59:32.236 --> 59:35.114
and to increase the sentences
of people who are in prison.

59:35.197 --> 59:39.326
I'm trying to think how you address it.
It's hard to address something that's like

59:39.409 --> 59:41.286
almost like folklore at this point.

59:41.370 --> 59:44.414
They are not doing anything
to really clean up that past

59:44.498 --> 59:47.167
or to address the real consequences
for real people

59:47.251 --> 59:48.918
of the extreme policies they've pushed.

59:49.002 --> 59:51.004
In fact, it doesn't talk about
its past history.

59:51.088 --> 59:55.008
I mean, it's hard for me
to even understand, uh,

59:55.092 --> 59:57.469
what they're even talking about.
A lot of it.

59:57.552 --> 01:00:00.805
CCA directly benefited,
directly profited from its investment

01:00:00.889 --> 01:00:03.057
in ALEC,
the American Legislative Exchange Council.

01:00:03.142 --> 01:00:06.520
And the American people, in many ways,
were harmed by these policies

01:00:06.603 --> 01:00:10.023
due to the mass incarceration
of people, particularly people of color.

01:00:10.107 --> 01:00:15.529
Look, right now our position
is that we want less people in prison.

01:00:15.612 --> 01:00:18.823
I don't think that helps the private
prison industry, quite frankly.

01:00:18.907 --> 01:00:20.367
I think myself and the lawmakers,

01:00:20.450 --> 01:00:23.828
we're just always looking for better,
innovative ways to run government.

01:00:23.912 --> 01:00:24.955
I think that's one thing

01:00:25.038 --> 01:00:27.878
as conservatives, who believe in
the free market and limited government,

01:00:27.916 --> 01:00:28.834
we pride ourselves on.

01:00:28.917 --> 01:00:31.211
We're supposed to be
the party of innovation.

01:00:32.045 --> 01:00:36.425
<i>Another bill
that ALEC innovated was SB 1070.</i>

01:00:36.508 --> 01:00:39.303
<i>CCA was on the ALEC task force
that pushed that law</i>

01:00:39.386 --> 01:00:41.763
<i>that gave police
the right to stop anyone</i>

01:00:41.846 --> 01:00:43.807
<i>they thought looked like an immigrant.</i>

01:00:45.642 --> 01:00:47.977
<i>This law filled
immigration detention facilities,</i>

01:00:48.061 --> 01:00:51.148
<i>and it directly benefited
an ALEC member, CCA.</i>

01:00:53.107 --> 01:00:56.695
CCA could potentially reap
huge financial benefits from SB 1070,

01:00:56.778 --> 01:01:01.241
since 1070 was designed to lock up
a lot more people in Arizona

01:01:01.325 --> 01:01:03.577
on federal immigration charges.
Cha-ching!

01:01:03.660 --> 01:01:07.206
<i>An influx of undocumented
immigrants, many of them children...</i>

01:01:07.289 --> 01:01:11.460
<i>In Arizona, Corrections
Corporation of America, or CCA,</i>

01:01:11.543 --> 01:01:14.713
<i>holds the federal contract
to house detained immigrants.</i>

01:01:14.796 --> 01:01:18.883
<i>It's worth more than $11 million
every month.</i>

01:01:20.594 --> 01:01:23.388
Our, uh, immigration facilities
are a disgrace.

01:01:23.472 --> 01:01:28.059
<i>There are families kept there,
uh, in horrible conditions.</i>

01:01:29.018 --> 01:01:32.231
They're called "detention facilities,"
but they're really prisons for immigrants.

01:01:32.314 --> 01:01:34.900
Calling them "detention facility"
doesn't make them not a prison.

01:01:34.983 --> 01:01:36.943
They're a prison.
They just have a different name.

01:01:37.026 --> 01:01:42.073
We're having what some people are saying
is a creation of a "crimmigration" system.

01:01:42.156 --> 01:01:45.702
That there's the merger
of our immigration enforcement

01:01:45.785 --> 01:01:47.954
and our law enforcement system.

01:01:48.037 --> 01:01:51.500
And so, that's some of the same things
that were used in the war on drugs,

01:01:51.583 --> 01:01:53.793
are now migrating to other populations.

01:01:53.877 --> 01:01:58.673
You heard it, uh, with Donald Trump,
not about blacks but with Mexicans.

01:01:58.757 --> 01:02:01.468
You know,
"Oh, well, they're rapists, murderers.

01:02:01.551 --> 01:02:04.137
Oh, and by the way,
some of 'em may be good people."

01:02:05.597 --> 01:02:08.225
Oh, boy. You know, where do you start
on something like that?

01:02:09.601 --> 01:02:13.897
<i>In late 2010, CCA left ALEC
after a big NPR story came out</i>

01:02:13.980 --> 01:02:17.108
<i>accusing ALEC of pushing SB 1070.</i>

01:02:17.442 --> 01:02:20.153
ALEC doesn't do anything on immigration.

01:02:20.237 --> 01:02:24.324
No. No which way. Not to the right,
not to the left. Nothing.

01:02:24.408 --> 01:02:27.160
So, I don't really have anything
for you on that one. Sorry.

01:02:27.244 --> 01:02:30.497
ALEC has recently made
what I would describe as a PR move

01:02:30.580 --> 01:02:32.624
to say that it's gonna be right on crime.

01:02:32.707 --> 01:02:36.044
That it's gonna be on the right side
of criminal justice policy and reform.

01:02:36.127 --> 01:02:41.466
That move comes in the wake of its loss
of a massive number of corporations.

01:02:42.842 --> 01:02:47.681
What ultimately happened is our board
looked at the issues that ALEC worked on

01:02:47.764 --> 01:02:50.183
and decided
that we don't do social issues,

01:02:50.267 --> 01:02:52.352
we're focused on economic issues.

01:02:52.436 --> 01:02:57.691
We jettisoned basically almost
all of our legislation that was pre-2007.

01:02:57.774 --> 01:03:00.694
So we basically...
Fresh slate going forward.

01:03:00.777 --> 01:03:02.570
A fresh start going forward.

01:03:03.154 --> 01:03:05.490
<i>This industry knows that it's dying...</i>

01:03:06.616 --> 01:03:10.620
and is actually preparing
for the next thing.

01:03:10.704 --> 01:03:14.416
And the animating factors that have
led to such a system like bail.

01:03:14.499 --> 01:03:19.379
We're always gonna see
new permutations of a cancer. Right?

01:03:19.463 --> 01:03:20.589
And that's what this is.

01:03:20.672 --> 01:03:23.550
And over the last couple years,
since 2008,

01:03:23.633 --> 01:03:27.637
we've been involved really
in a wholesale reform effort,

01:03:27.721 --> 01:03:32.559
where 31 states have now adopted
positive changes on sentencing,

01:03:32.642 --> 01:03:34.728
on parole and probation reforms.

01:03:34.811 --> 01:03:38.565
ALEC has a concerted effort to privatize
almost every aspect of government,

01:03:38.648 --> 01:03:40.775
but we had no idea
that they were also aiming

01:03:40.859 --> 01:03:43.361
<i>to try to privatize probation and parole.</i>

01:03:43.653 --> 01:03:47.073
ALEC is no longer concerned
about CCA and CCA's interest.

01:03:47.156 --> 01:03:49.618
CCA no longer has
a seat at the table with ALEC,

01:03:49.701 --> 01:03:52.746
so it doesn't have a financial interest
in advancing policies

01:03:52.829 --> 01:03:55.164
<i>that increase the profits of CCA.</i>

01:03:55.248 --> 01:03:57.709
<i>But the American Bail Coalition
is still part of ALEC.</i>

01:03:57.792 --> 01:04:00.504
Today, our state penitentiaries

01:04:00.587 --> 01:04:05.008
are filled to the brim
and overflowing with inmates.

01:04:05.091 --> 01:04:07.886
<i>When I think
of systems of oppression,</i>

01:04:07.969 --> 01:04:11.973
uh, historically, in this country
and elsewhere, they're durable.

01:04:12.056 --> 01:04:15.309
And they tend to reinvent themselves,
and they do it right under your nose.

01:04:15.394 --> 01:04:18.062
One of the things they want to do
is GPS monitoring.

01:04:18.146 --> 01:04:21.358
Having a home confinement system
for juveniles, I think, is a great thing

01:04:21.441 --> 01:04:24.318
'cause it forces the parents
to take responsibility and step up.

01:04:24.403 --> 01:04:27.822
Prisons would be
more embedded in our homes.

01:04:27.906 --> 01:04:30.266
Some of them would be monitored
on GPS and things like that.

01:04:30.324 --> 01:04:34.621
So folks won't be locked up in a cage,
in a cell, inside of an institution,

01:04:34.704 --> 01:04:37.832
but they will have ankle bracelets on.
They'll have wrist bracelets on.

01:04:37.916 --> 01:04:40.960
Would that help to solve
the prison overcrowding problem?

01:04:41.044 --> 01:04:42.211
Absolutely.

01:04:42.295 --> 01:04:46.425
And what I worry about is that
we fall asleep at the wheel and wake up,

01:04:46.508 --> 01:04:49.302
and realize that we may not
have people in prisons

01:04:49.386 --> 01:04:51.304
in rural communities all over America,

01:04:51.388 --> 01:04:54.182
but that we're incarcerating people
right in their communities.

01:04:54.265 --> 01:04:57.852
That is what I see,
what a lot of the focus is on,

01:04:57.936 --> 01:04:59.270
is taking people from prison,

01:04:59.353 --> 01:05:01.690
putting them in community corrections
parole and probation,

01:05:01.773 --> 01:05:04.275
and really investing in those programs.

01:05:04.358 --> 01:05:05.819
How much progress is it really,

01:05:05.902 --> 01:05:10.657
if communities of color are still under
perpetual surveillance and control,

01:05:10.740 --> 01:05:15.662
but now there's a private company
making money off the GPS monitor,

01:05:15.745 --> 01:05:18.623
rather than the person
being locked in a literal cage?

01:05:18.707 --> 01:05:21.751
If we can help you...

01:05:23.253 --> 01:05:26.464
save crime victims
in your legislative district...

01:05:28.007 --> 01:05:29.926
you don't mind me making a dollar.

01:05:31.219 --> 01:05:34.973
<i>And so, ALEC continues
to be a body that,</i>

01:05:35.056 --> 01:05:37.183
<i>while it may have some
really strong rhetoric</i>

01:05:37.266 --> 01:05:41.145
on why it supports
crime reform now, suddenly,

01:05:41.229 --> 01:05:42.772
uh, sort of out of the blue,

01:05:42.856 --> 01:05:45.442
it actually has real financial interests.

01:05:45.525 --> 01:05:47.193
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

01:05:48.778 --> 01:05:53.032
If you're in the prison business,
uh, you don't want reform.

01:05:53.116 --> 01:05:54.476
You may say you do, but you don't.

01:05:54.534 --> 01:05:57.871
And there are a bunch of people out there
desperately trying to make sure

01:05:57.954 --> 01:06:00.874
that that prison population
does not drop one person,

01:06:00.957 --> 01:06:03.835
because their economic model needs that.

01:06:03.918 --> 01:06:09.591
Prison industrial complex refers
to the system of mass incarceration

01:06:09.674 --> 01:06:12.426
and companies that profit
from mass incarceration.

01:06:12.511 --> 01:06:14.763
<i>That includes
both operators of private prisons,</i>

01:06:14.846 --> 01:06:20.184
<i>which get a lot of attention,
as well as a vast sea of vendors.</i>

01:06:20.268 --> 01:06:24.397
From SECURUS Technologies,
that supplies telephone services,

01:06:24.481 --> 01:06:27.817
that made $114 million
in profits last year...

01:06:27.901 --> 01:06:32.280
Those calls to family and friends are
costing a pretty penny in state prisons.

01:06:32.363 --> 01:06:36.242
They inflate the price that they charge
the inmate and the inmate's family.

01:06:36.325 --> 01:06:39.037
<i>For example, in Maryland,
if you earn minimum wage,</i>

01:06:39.120 --> 01:06:42.791
<i>you'd have to work an hour and a half
to afford a ten minute phone call.</i>

01:06:46.169 --> 01:06:50.339
<i>There's also Aramark,
one of the big food service providers.</i>

01:06:50.924 --> 01:06:53.009
<i>In more than one state,
they have been accused</i>

01:06:53.092 --> 01:06:55.887
<i>of having maggots in the food
that they've served.</i>

01:06:59.015 --> 01:07:03.394
Corizon Healthcare provides healthcare
services in 28 different states.

01:07:03.477 --> 01:07:05.855
Multimillion-dollar contracts
for this service.

01:07:05.939 --> 01:07:11.235
Huge incentives given to contractors
for very long contracts,

01:07:11.319 --> 01:07:13.822
so it's actually a disincentive
to provide the service,

01:07:13.905 --> 01:07:15.657
because you're going to be paid anyway.

01:07:22.455 --> 01:07:24.332
One of the reasons it's so difficult

01:07:24.415 --> 01:07:27.710
to talk about mass incarceration
in this country, and to question it,

01:07:27.794 --> 01:07:31.548
is because it has become
so heavily monetized.

01:07:31.631 --> 01:07:33.675
A little company called UNICOR,

01:07:33.758 --> 01:07:36.678
<i>that does $900 million
in business annually.</i>

01:07:36.761 --> 01:07:38.471
How do they do it?

01:07:38.555 --> 01:07:40.264
Volume.

01:07:40.348 --> 01:07:42.433
<i>- Also, prison labor.</i>

01:07:42.517 --> 01:07:45.270
<i>Partnerships between
