01:21:56.704 --> 01:21:59.832
<i>and Americans should remember that,
if we're going to have law and order.</i>

01:22:01.208 --> 01:22:06.922
I am...
the law and order candidate.

01:22:09.842 --> 01:22:13.762
We thought... I mean,
they called the end of slavery "jubilee."

01:22:13.846 --> 01:22:15.597
We thought we were done then.

01:22:15.806 --> 01:22:19.142
And then you had 100 years
of Jim Crow, terror and lynching.

01:22:20.352 --> 01:22:24.022
Dr. King, these guys come on the scene,
Ella Jo Baker, Fannie Lou Hamer,

01:22:24.106 --> 01:22:26.191
we get the bills passed to vote,

01:22:26.274 --> 01:22:28.026
and then they break out the handcuffs.

01:22:28.110 --> 01:22:31.363
Label you felon,
you can't vote or get a job.

01:22:31.447 --> 01:22:35.534
So, we don't know
what the next iteration of this will be,

01:22:35.617 --> 01:22:38.036
but it will be. It will be.

01:22:38.120 --> 01:22:39.788
And we will have to be vigilant.

01:23:03.646 --> 01:23:08.734
<i>The Bureau of Justice reported
That one in three young, black males</i>

01:23:08.817 --> 01:23:11.361
<i>is expected to go to jail or prison
during his lifetime,</i>

01:23:11.444 --> 01:23:14.364
<i>which is
an unbelievably shocking statistic.</i>

01:23:22.289 --> 01:23:26.251
<i>Black men account
for roughly 6.5% of the US population.</i>

01:23:26.334 --> 01:23:30.213
<i>They make up 40.2%
of the prison population.</i>

01:23:34.259 --> 01:23:37.763
We now have more African Americans
under criminal supervision

01:23:37.846 --> 01:23:39.890
than all the slaves back in the 1850s.

01:23:39.973 --> 01:23:42.810
The prison industrial complex, uh...

01:23:42.893 --> 01:23:47.480
relies historically
on the inheritances of slavery.

01:23:50.192 --> 01:23:51.860
<i>The 13th Amendment says,</i>

01:23:51.944 --> 01:23:55.739
<i>"No involuntary servitude except for those
who have been duly convicted of a crime."</i>

01:23:55.823 --> 01:23:59.702
<i>So once you've been convicted of a crime,
you are in essence a slave of the state.</i>

01:24:01.203 --> 01:24:03.831
The stroke of a pen is not self-enforcing.

01:24:03.914 --> 01:24:07.034
And so, while the 13th Amendment is hailed
as this great milestone for freedom,

01:24:07.084 --> 01:24:10.879
and abolitionists celebrate,
and this is the end of a lifelong quest,

01:24:10.963 --> 01:24:12.673
the reality is much more problematic.

01:24:12.756 --> 01:24:16.051
Well, once that clause is inserted
in there, it becomes a tool.

01:24:16.134 --> 01:24:18.220
It's there.
It's embedded in the structure.

01:24:18.303 --> 01:24:22.808
And for those who seek to use
this criminality clause as a tool,

01:24:22.891 --> 01:24:25.602
it can become a pretty powerful one,
because it's privileged.

01:24:25.686 --> 01:24:28.355
It's in the constitution,
it's the supreme law of the land.

01:24:30.899 --> 01:24:33.110
Throughout American history,

01:24:33.193 --> 01:24:35.988
African Americans
have repeatedly been controlled

01:24:36.071 --> 01:24:39.908
through systems of racial
and social control that appear to die,

01:24:39.992 --> 01:24:42.327
but then are reborn in new form,

01:24:42.410 --> 01:24:44.997
tailored to the needs and constraints
of the time.

01:24:45.080 --> 01:24:46.999
<i>You know, after the collapse of slavery,</i>

01:24:47.082 --> 01:24:50.252
<i>a new system was born,
convict leasing,</i>

01:24:50.335 --> 01:24:53.631
<i>which was a new form of slavery.</i>

01:24:54.882 --> 01:24:59.261
<i>And once convict leasing faded away,
a new system was born,</i>

01:24:59.344 --> 01:25:00.804
<i>a Jim Crow system,</i>

01:25:00.888 --> 01:25:06.268
<i>that relegated African Americans
to a permanent second-class status.</i>

01:25:07.686 --> 01:25:08.812
<i>And here we are,</i>

01:25:08.896 --> 01:25:12.399
<i>decades after the collapse
of the old Jim Crow,</i>

01:25:12.482 --> 01:25:15.694
<i>and a new system
has been born again in America.</i>

01:25:15.778 --> 01:25:19.197
A system of mass incarceration
that, once again,

01:25:19.281 --> 01:25:21.825
strips millions of poor people,

01:25:21.909 --> 01:25:24.161
overwhelmingly poor people of color,

01:25:24.244 --> 01:25:27.915
of the very rights supposedly won
in the civil rights movement.

01:25:27.998 --> 01:25:30.417
And so instead of talking about it,

01:25:30.500 --> 01:25:32.085
we just tried to move on.

01:25:32.169 --> 01:25:34.963
After the Civil Rights Act was passed
and after the civil rights laws,

01:25:35.047 --> 01:25:36.423
we tried to play it off.

01:25:36.506 --> 01:25:37.746
Because we didn't deal with it,

01:25:37.800 --> 01:25:40.385
that narrative
of racial difference continued.

01:25:40.468 --> 01:25:44.181
And it turned into this presumption
of dangerousness and guilt

01:25:44.264 --> 01:25:47.267
that follows every black and brown person
wherever they are.

01:25:51.063 --> 01:25:53.899
<i>You need to get out
of the street immediately.</i>

01:25:53.982 --> 01:25:55.358
Get out of the way!

01:25:58.195 --> 01:25:59.988
This is St. Louis County Police.

01:26:00.072 --> 01:26:01.448
Stay off the roadway.

01:26:01.949 --> 01:26:05.243
<i>Ferguson was not simply
about Mike Brown.</i>

01:26:05.327 --> 01:26:11.166
It was also this pattern of mass
criminalization and mass incarceration.

01:26:12.167 --> 01:26:14.544
Back off. Back off.

01:26:15.170 --> 01:26:18.674
There was an average of three warrants
per household in Ferguson.

01:26:19.800 --> 01:26:22.678
<i>And so people rose up
because they understood</i>

01:26:22.761 --> 01:26:27.515
<i>that they were also enemies of the state,
seen as enemies of the state.</i>

01:26:29.517 --> 01:26:34.272
<i>The communities in which black people live
really become occupied territories,</i>

01:26:34.356 --> 01:26:40.112
and black people have become seen
as, um, enemy combatants, right,

01:26:40.195 --> 01:26:42.072
who don't have any rights,

01:26:42.155 --> 01:26:45.658
and who can be stopped and frisked

01:26:45.743 --> 01:26:48.996
and, you know, arrested
and detained and questioned

01:26:49.079 --> 01:26:50.706
and killed with impunity.

01:26:57.004 --> 01:26:59.089
<i>If we were to look at</i>

01:26:59.172 --> 01:27:03.676
the larger-scale riots that we know of
in, you know, our recent history,

01:27:03.761 --> 01:27:05.303
<i>from Rodney King,</i>

01:27:05.387 --> 01:27:07.765
<i>to the Detroit riot in 1967,</i>

01:27:07.848 --> 01:27:09.766
<i>the Newark riot in 1967,</i>

01:27:09.850 --> 01:27:13.437
<i>Harlem riot in 1964,
Watts in 1965.</i>

01:27:13.520 --> 01:27:16.940
Every single one of those riots
was a result of police brutality.

01:27:17.024 --> 01:27:18.064
That is the common thread.

01:27:18.108 --> 01:27:21.737
- Fight back! Fight back!
- Fist up! Fist up!

01:27:21.820 --> 01:27:25.907
<i>It would be a mistake to say,
as many do in the current context,</i>

01:27:25.991 --> 01:27:28.827
<i>that if you're against the police,
then you're against law and order.</i>

01:27:28.910 --> 01:27:32.247
<i>These are hardworking civil servants
putting their lives on the line every day.</i>

01:27:32.330 --> 01:27:33.331
<i>And that's true.</i>

01:27:33.415 --> 01:27:37.669
<i>People who join the police do so,
you know, to do these sorts of things.</i>

01:27:38.670 --> 01:27:44.092
But if you dismiss black complaints
of mistreatment by police

01:27:44.176 --> 01:27:46.344
as being completely rooted
in our modern context,

01:27:46.428 --> 01:27:48.068
then you're missing the point completely.

01:27:48.138 --> 01:27:50.348
There has never been
a period in our history

01:27:50.432 --> 01:27:56.229
where the law and order branch
of the state has not operated against

01:27:56.313 --> 01:27:59.817
the freedoms, the liberties,
the options, the choices

01:27:59.900 --> 01:28:02.903
that have been available for
the black community, generally speaking.

01:28:02.986 --> 01:28:07.825
And to ignore that racial heritage,
to ignore that historical context,

01:28:07.908 --> 01:28:09.868
means that you can't have
an informed debate

01:28:09.952 --> 01:28:13.288
about the current state
of blacks and police relationship today,

01:28:13.371 --> 01:28:15.248
'cause this didn't just appear
out of nothing.

01:28:15.332 --> 01:28:18.376
This is the product
of a centuries-long historical process.

01:28:18.460 --> 01:28:22.047
And to not reckon with that
is to shut off solutions.

01:28:22.130 --> 01:28:25.675
We may have lost the sheets
of the Ku Klux Klan,

01:28:25.758 --> 01:28:28.887
but, clearly, when you see
black kids being shot down...

01:28:29.471 --> 01:28:32.808
then, obviously,
we didn't cut out this cancer.

01:28:34.852 --> 01:28:36.228
For many of us, you know,

01:28:36.311 --> 01:28:39.147
whose families
lived through this,

01:28:39.231 --> 01:28:41.691
who are extensions
of this kind of oppression,

01:28:41.774 --> 01:28:44.652
we don't need to see pictures
to understand what's going on.

01:28:44.736 --> 01:28:47.865
It's really to kind of, like,
speak to the masses

01:28:47.948 --> 01:28:50.325
who have been ignoring this
for the majority of their life.

01:28:50.408 --> 01:28:53.411
But I also think there's trouble
of just showing,

01:28:53.495 --> 01:28:56.414
you know,
black bodies as dead bodies, too.

01:28:56.498 --> 01:28:59.751
Too much of anything
becomes unhealthy, unuseful.

01:29:00.961 --> 01:29:05.298
I think they need to be seen,
if the family is okay with it.

01:29:05.841 --> 01:29:09.761
It wasn't until things were made visual
in the civil rights movement,

01:29:09.845 --> 01:29:12.555
that we really saw, uh,

01:29:12.639 --> 01:29:16.518
folks come out
and being shocked into movement.

01:29:16.601 --> 01:29:19.646
You have to shock people
into paying attention.

01:29:19.729 --> 01:29:23.566
But there's a kind of historical
trajectory that we can trace here, um,

01:29:23.650 --> 01:29:25.818
through media and technology.

01:29:25.903 --> 01:29:29.156
We went back to, um, the slavery era,

01:29:29.239 --> 01:29:32.450
when people were writing autobiographies
or slave narratives.

01:29:34.202 --> 01:29:35.828
<i>Later in the 19th century,</i>

01:29:35.913 --> 01:29:37.455
when people began to use photographs

01:29:37.539 --> 01:29:39.374
<i>and they showed images.</i>

01:29:40.500 --> 01:29:43.420
<i>There's a famous image
of slave Gordon and his back,</i>

01:29:43.503 --> 01:29:46.839
<i>and you can see just this
kind of lattice of scar tissue</i>

01:29:46.924 --> 01:29:50.552
<i>that is evidence of the whippings
that he received.</i>

01:29:50.635 --> 01:29:54.681
<i>Or the images of lynchings,
which white people produced.</i>

01:29:56.599 --> 01:29:59.477
<i>The murder of Emmett Till
was really thought of as being</i>

01:29:59.561 --> 01:30:02.898
<i>one of the primary catalysts
for the civil rights movement.</i>

01:30:04.024 --> 01:30:06.109
<i>The willingness of his mother</i>

01:30:06.193 --> 01:30:09.612
<i>to have an open-casket funeral.</i>

01:30:12.365 --> 01:30:15.994
<i>Hundreds and hundreds
of black folks filed past</i>

01:30:16.078 --> 01:30:18.205
<i>and see this young boy</i>

01:30:18.288 --> 01:30:21.458
<i>who had been killed
by white supremacists in the South.</i>

01:30:23.376 --> 01:30:26.964
<i>To publish those photographs
in black publications</i>

01:30:27.047 --> 01:30:31.801
<i>so the entire black world, like
our Facebook or our Twitter now, right?</i>

01:30:31.884 --> 01:30:35.722
<i>So that the whole black world
could see what had happened.</i>

01:30:35.805 --> 01:30:39.934
In the 1950s, Dr. King
and the civil rights movement

01:30:40.018 --> 01:30:41.269
used television in this way.

01:30:41.353 --> 01:30:43.480
<i>"Look, this is what segregation
looks like.</i>

01:30:43.563 --> 01:30:47.484
<i>These are dogs attacking children.
These are people being fire hosed."</i>

01:30:49.402 --> 01:30:54.241
<i>Searching for the medium of technology,
that will confirm your experience</i>

01:30:54.324 --> 01:30:57.119
such that your basic humanity
can be recognized.

01:30:57.202 --> 01:31:00.330
The difference now is
somebody can hold up one of these,

01:31:00.413 --> 01:31:01.748
get what's going on.

01:31:01.831 --> 01:31:06.336
They can put it on YouTube,
and the whole world has to deal with it.

01:31:06.419 --> 01:31:07.629
That's what's new.

01:31:07.712 --> 01:31:10.007
It's not the protest.
It's not the brutality.

01:31:10.090 --> 01:31:12.509
It's the fact that we can force
a conversation about it.

01:31:12.592 --> 01:31:16.596
We have been consistently been murdered
as a result of police aggression.

01:31:16.679 --> 01:31:20.600
They generally would excuse it
by calling us criminals.

01:31:21.268 --> 01:31:23.270
<i>When they was killing Oscar Grant...</i>

01:31:30.443 --> 01:31:32.279
When they got to Eric Garner...

01:31:32.862 --> 01:31:34.531
I can't breathe.

01:31:34.614 --> 01:31:35.865
I can't breathe.

01:31:35.948 --> 01:31:38.618
I can't breathe.
I can't breathe.

01:31:38.701 --> 01:31:40.078
I can't breathe.

01:31:40.162 --> 01:31:42.539
I can't breathe.
I can't breathe.

01:31:42.622 --> 01:31:44.582
<i>Everyone pointed out
that he was saying,</i>

01:31:44.666 --> 01:31:46.418
<i>"I can't breathe.
I can't breathe."</i>

01:31:46.501 --> 01:31:48.211
But the sentences before that were,

01:31:48.295 --> 01:31:50.505
"Why are you always stopping me?

01:31:50.588 --> 01:31:55.468
Why is it, day in and day out,
week in and week out, you're stopping me?"

01:31:55.552 --> 01:31:58.930
And that, I think, is hugely important.

01:31:59.013 --> 01:32:02.975
When we think about the children
who were killed at the hands of the state,

01:32:03.060 --> 01:32:06.313
I think about Tamir Rice at 12 years old,

01:32:06.396 --> 01:32:09.941
<i>and the way that he was killed,
you know, it hits my heart.</i>

01:32:10.900 --> 01:32:14.154
Go ahead and take
your seat belt off. Stop. Stop!

01:32:22.995 --> 01:32:24.164
You good?

01:32:30.128 --> 01:32:32.672
- Roll on your stomach. Now!
- Stop fighting!

01:32:35.217 --> 01:32:38.345
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
- Oh, shit.

01:32:38.428 --> 01:32:41.306
He shot me, man. I was shot.

01:32:41.389 --> 01:32:43.016
He didn't do shit.
You didn't.

01:32:43.099 --> 01:32:45.685
- I'm losing breath.
- Fuck your breath.

01:32:45.768 --> 01:32:47.437
Stay with me.

01:32:47.520 --> 01:32:50.773
We got pulled over
for a busted taillight in the back.

01:33:17.342 --> 01:33:18.968
<i>Police violence,</i>

01:33:19.051 --> 01:33:21.888
<i>that isn't the problem
in and of itself.</i>

01:33:21.971 --> 01:33:26.017
It's reflection of a much larger,
brutal system

01:33:26.100 --> 01:33:29.604
of racial and social control
known as mass incarceration,

01:33:29.687 --> 01:33:33.608
which authorizes
this kind of police violence.

01:33:33.691 --> 01:33:36.653
That's why, for me,
the brilliance of Black Lives Matter...

01:33:36.736 --> 01:33:41.574
They have a distributed leadership model.
You can't find their address.

01:33:41.658 --> 01:33:44.661
I mean, Black Lives Matter
is not a stoppable phenomenon,

01:33:44.744 --> 01:33:46.454
by a bullet or anything else.

01:33:46.538 --> 01:33:48.415
And so, there's hope there
because of that.

01:33:49.081 --> 01:33:51.543
Having people truly understand

01:33:51.626 --> 01:33:54.379
that when black lives matter,

01:33:55.046 --> 01:33:57.006
everybody's life matters,

01:33:57.089 --> 01:34:02.011
including every single person
that enters this criminal justice system

01:34:02.094 --> 01:34:04.096
and this prison industrial complex.

01:34:04.181 --> 01:34:07.058
It's not just even about
only black lives, right?

01:34:07.141 --> 01:34:11.646
<i>It's about changing the way
this country understands human dignity.</i>

01:34:24.951 --> 01:34:28.580
<i>That's what, really,
this Black Lives Matter moment is about.</i>

01:34:28.663 --> 01:34:33.125
<i>This question of whose life
do we recognize as valuable?</i>

01:34:45.513 --> 01:34:48.558
<i>The opposite of criminalization
is humanization.</i>

01:34:48.641 --> 01:34:51.477
<i>That's the one thing I hope
that people will understand.</i>

01:34:53.020 --> 01:34:56.608
It's about rehumanizing us,
as a people,

01:34:56.691 --> 01:34:59.652
and us, right, as a people,
all of us.

01:35:08.245 --> 01:35:11.414
The system of mass incarceration
has grown,

01:35:11.498 --> 01:35:14.417
and sprawled and developed an appetite

01:35:14.501 --> 01:35:19.088
that is gobbling up people
in communities of all colors.

01:35:19.171 --> 01:35:20.757
But if it hadn't been for the fact

01:35:20.840 --> 01:35:25.553
that it began with a group of people
defined by race,

01:35:25.637 --> 01:35:28.848
that we as a nation
have learned not to care about,

01:35:28.931 --> 01:35:33.603
we wouldn't be talking about
two million people behind bars today.

01:35:33.686 --> 01:35:34.729
People say all the time,

01:35:34.812 --> 01:35:37.148
"I don't understand how people
could've tolerated slavery."

01:35:37.231 --> 01:35:39.359
How could they have made peace with that?

01:35:39.442 --> 01:35:43.280
How could people have gone to a lynching
and participated in that?

01:35:43.363 --> 01:35:47.074
How did people make sense
of the segregation,

01:35:47.158 --> 01:35:50.286
this white and colored-only drinking...
That's so crazy.

01:35:50.370 --> 01:35:54.374
"If I was living at that time, I would
have never tolerated anything like that."

01:35:54.457 --> 01:35:57.752
And the truth is, we are living
at this time, and we are tolerating it.

